The warmest months on Caldey Island typically occur in July and August, with mean daily maximum temperatures reaching approximately 20 °C (68 °F). Conversely, the coldest period is generally from December through February, where mean daily maximums hover around 8 °C (46 °F) and mean daily minimums drop to about 3 °C (37 °F). Extreme temperatures have been recorded, with the absolute maximum reaching a rather sweltering 33 °C (91 °F) in August, and the absolute minimum plummeting to a brisk −9 °C (16 °F) in February, proving that even "cold islands" can surprise you. Wind speeds also vary seasonally, with October generally experiencing the highest maximum recorded wind speeds at 67 km/h (42 mph), while the summer months of July and August tend to be calmer, with maximums around 43-46 km/h (27-29 mph).

## Wildlife

Caldey Island, despite its small footprint, serves as a remarkable bastion for a diverse array of flora and fauna. It is particularly renowned for its vibrant display of flowers, many of which are considered rare and are seldom encountered in other regions of the United Kingdom, a testament to its unique ecological conditions. Furthermore, the island becomes a bustling hub for numerous bird species during the summer months, offering a dynamic spectacle for ornithologists and casual observers alike.

A particularly significant avian feature is located on [St Margaret's Island](/St_Margaret%27s_Island), which hosts the country's largest colony of [cormorants](/Great_cormorant). These dark, diving birds are a formidable presence, dominating the rocky shores. In a concerted effort to enhance the island's biodiversity and ecological balance, a two-year rat eradication program was meticulously carried out. Following its successful completion, [red squirrels](/Red_squirrel) were carefully reintroduced to Caldey in 2016. This reintroduction proved to be a success story, with reports by 2018 confirming that the squirrels were breeding successfully. The population has since thrived, with an estimated 50 individuals now inhabiting the island, a small victory in the ongoing struggle for ecological restoration.

## Economy and services

The economic pulse of Caldey Island is primarily sustained by a rather unique blend of spiritual tourism and the diligent production of goods for sale, predominantly artisanal chocolate and fragrances. While the island does offer a certain tranquility, it is, like everything else, subject to the demands of commerce. Tourism undeniably forms the bedrock of its income, drawing visitors seeking both spiritual solace and unique products. Recognizing the inexorable march of modernity, the monastery rather pragmatically launched an Internet shop in 2001, allowing their distinctive products to reach a wider audience beyond the island's shores. Their lavender perfume, in particular, has garnered considerable acclaim, with the renowned perfume critic [Luca Turin](/Luca_Turin) famously declaring it "simply the best lavender soliflore on earth," a rather high praise for a monastic endeavor.

Beyond commerce, Caldey Island actively functions as a [spiritual retreat](/Retreat_(spiritual)), offering solace and contemplation to guests. This facility is capable of accommodating up to 750 guests annually, a testament to its enduring appeal. The retreat is currently undergoing an extensive refurbishment, with plans for its reopening scheduled for Easter 2024, promising an enhanced experience for future visitors.

The island also maintains a fully functioning post office, a rather quaint anachronism, which includes a museum dedicated to the island's rich and peculiar history. In a further display of its unique autonomy, Caldey Island issues its own postage stamps and even boasts its own monetary unit, whimsically named after the local fish, the [dab](/Common_dab). For more mundane earthly pleasures, a colonial-style tea shop offers refreshments on the village green. The island's vital water supply is secured by an underground reservoir situated near the lighthouse, fed by a natural spring, ensuring sustenance for both the monastic gardens and the island's inhabitants.

In terms of emergency preparedness, the island demonstrates a rather pragmatic, if somewhat lean, approach. A single [Land Rover](/Land_Rover) serves a tripartite function, shared between the fire service, the coastguard, and the local police, embodying a spirit of communal resourcefulness. A volunteer fire service, operating under the aegis of the [Mid and West Wales Fire and Rescue Service](/Mid_and_West_Wales_Fire_and_Rescue_Service), is on standby, equipped with access to two [fire engines](/Fire_engine). One of these is a robust 4x4 rural firefighting unit, which required the rather dramatic intervention of the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) to be airlifted onto the island. The last significant fire reported on the island occurred in 1940, resulting in damage to the monastery, a stark reminder of the ever-present risks.

For the logistical challenge of moving heavier items or livestock to and from the mainland, the island relies on two essential cranes: one strategically located at [Tenby Harbour](/Tenby_Harbour) and the other positioned on the island itself. Furthermore, the island possesses a modest collection of basic farming equipment, including two tractors, which are indispensable for the ongoing upkeep of the land and the transportation of goods, ensuring that even a holy island maintains a practical side.

## Landmarks

Caldey Island, for those who choose to visit, offers a selection of landmarks that speak to its layered history and spiritual significance. These are not merely structures, but rather echoes of centuries past, if one cares to listen. Among the notable tourist attractions, one can find the recently restored 13th-century church of [St Illtyd](/Illtud), a testament to enduring faith and persistent craftsmanship. Also present is a remarkable [ogham](/Ogham) cross dating back to the 6th century, a tangible link to ancient Celtic heritage, alongside a quaint [Norman](/Norman_architecture) chapel. Dominating the landscape, of course, is [Caldey Abbey](/Caldey_Abbey), the current monastic heart of the island, which reached its completion in 1910.

The [Caldey Lighthouse](/Caldey_Lighthouse), an imposing structure, was originally constructed in 1829. Its primary purpose was to aid coastal traffic, particularly vessels involved in the trade of limestone and coal navigating towards mid- and North [Wales](/Wales). However, its strategic position also served a broader, more critical function: assisting long-distance and North American shipping in accurately identifying the entrance to the [Bristol Channel](/Bristol_Channel), thereby preventing potentially disastrous confusion with the [English Channel](/English_Channel). The lighthouse itself is characterized by its squat, round, brick-lined [limestone](/Limestone) [tower](/Tower), standing at a height of 17 meters (56 feet). Its construction is robust, with walls measuring 0.9 meters (3 feet) thick at the base, tapering slightly to 2 feet 6 inches (0.76 meters) thick at the summit. The light source is positioned at an elevation of 64 meters (210 feet) above the high-water mark, ensuring its visibility across the maritime expanse. The lighthouse underwent automation in 1929, bringing an end to the era of constant human attendance. The former oil store, a functional necessity for the lighthouse's operation, is now recognized as a [listed structure](/Listed_building), preserved for its historical significance. Flanking the lighthouse itself are the [lighthouse keeper](/Lighthouse_keeper)'s cottages, distinguished by their two-storey construction, hipped roofs, and distinctive octagonal chimneys. A single-storey linking corridor connects these residences, which were constructed around 1868–70 under the supervision of T. C. Harvey.